 nationalist agenda over a proselytizing one shapes their activist involvement.Ben Shitrit shows how women construct "frames of exception" that temporarily suspend, rather than challenge, some of the limiting aspects of their movements' gender ideology. Viewing women as agents in such movements, she analyzes the ways in which activists use nationalism to astutely reframe gender role transgressions from inappropriate to righteous. The author engages the literature on women's agency in Muslim and Jewish religious contexts, and sheds light on the centrality of women's activism to the promotion of the spiritual, social, cultural, and political agendas of both the Israeli and Palestinian religious right.Looking at the four most influential political movements of the Israeli and Palestinian religious right, Righteous Transgressions reveals how the bounds of gender expectations can be crossed for the political good.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIslam and politicszGaza Strip. 0aIslam and politicszIsrael. 0aIslam and politicszWest Bank. 0aJudaism and politicszIsrael. 0aReligious rightzGaza Strip. 0aReligious rightzIsrael. 0aReligious rightzWest Bank. 0aSocial sciencesxPolitical SciencexPolitical Science, other. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzGaza Strip. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzIsrael. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzWest Bank. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400873845zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400873845423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400873845.jpg  a978-3-11-063859-2  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  